  <h1 class="hidetitle">On the Evolution of Program State</h1> 
  <h2>Larger-scoped forces <br />shaping software engineering safety</h2> 
  <h3>Paul Vixie</h3> 
  <p>The state of a running computer program can be modeled as a discrete system containing a changing collection of variables and effectors having some combination of values and configurations. Any such collection constitutes a program state identity of which a countable quantity is <i>defined</i>. Superset collections, or collections having other values or configurations, are, by exclusion, <i>undefined</i>. As we consider program correctness, it is natural to focus on well-illuminated topics such as memory safety, but the full tapestry of software-related risks is much larger. This article considers the implications of defined versus undefined program states, as well as actions taken in light of those implications and in light of the certainty that the value of the world's online estate and therefore the cost of digital mistakes will never again be as low as it is today.</p> 
  <p>&nbsp;</p> 
  <h3>Taxonomy</h3> 
  <p>For the purpose of this discussion, a computer program has some containment domain, which might be an operating-system kernel managing a set of hardware resources connected to a computer, or might be a process, thread, or lambda hosted by such a system, or might even be a user-defined macro, script, or agent hosted within such a process, thread, or lambda. We could also reason about distributed systems of cooperating programs whose containment domain is the network itself, but distributed systems and their essential asynchrony are not explored further in this article.</p> 
  <p>Each state variable has a lifetime such as scoped, heap, static, or stored; each of the currently live variables can be said to have a value that is either defined or undefined. Scoped variables mostly reside on the stack, created as the stack grows, destroyed as it shrinks. Heap variables are long lived, lasting from allocation until destruction or program exit. Static variables are mostly long lived, lasting from program start until program exit. Stored variables are persistent across program start/stop cycles and last from creation until destruction or else forever. We say <i>mostly</i> for scoped and static variables, since a common software optimization technique is to store some variables in machine-level CPU registers rather than in addressable memory, and a common hardware optimization technique is to store frequently accessed memory contents in a cache and thus with an address but not residing fully in main memory.</p> 
  <p>State effectors can be purely imperative if the program's logic is internally driven or partially triggered if activated by external events such as elapsed time, channel input or readiness, or changes to the operating environment such as to the file system or other stored data. Individual operations of an effector might be machine-level CPU instructions; high-level language statements; or semi-opaque library or system calls, which are in turn implemented using instructions, statements, or further opaque calls. Some effectors exhibit only nonstateful behavior such as sending a message on a channel or sending a signal to some other program, but, in those cases, there can be a state change elsewhere.</p> 
  <p>Abstraction layers are made to hide implementation details that aren't relevant to a relying party or that are necessarily nonportable. For example, a function call in a high-level language might generate machine-level instructions to save some machine-level CPU registers—including the program counter on the stack (a <i>stack frame</i>)—and jump into the first instruction of the called function. Where that function's eventual return is effected by some generated instructions to restore those saved CPU registers from the stack, including the old program counter, this will cause execution to continue immediately after the function call.</p> 
  <p>Similarly, a heap might be implemented by storing the size of an object in the heap itself "just below" the allocated object, so that upon that object's release, its size need not be known by the relying party. These variables can be described as "hidden" behind an abstraction barrier. Such hidden variables are part of a program's state even though visible only to the underlying implementation. As such, these hidden variables contribute to the definedness of the overall program state, even if not directly inspectable by all parts of the program. If modified by means of a defect or vulnerability, the program can and usually does enter an undefined state.</p> 
  <p>A program can also enter an undefined state by means of a logic error affecting only visible variables. Consider, for example, a function whose return value is an enumeration and where the relying party does not properly interpret every possible enumerated value. This defect may take the form of a mismodality such that only conditions <i>equal to x</i> and <i>not equal to x</i> are handled, but not all values <i>not equal to x</i> mean the same thing or require the same treatment. Here, the set of values <i>not equal to x</i> includes at least one undefined value in the context of the relying party. Correcting this defect might require deliberately ignoring some values, signaling an error up-stack for some values, or aborting the program without fanfare on some values. The common refrain is that corrective necessary action (or inaction) must be deliberate.</p> 
  <p>&nbsp;</p> 
  <h3>Evolution</h3> 
  <p>Inevitably, to perform useful work, a program's state must evolve over time. Each evolutionary step is an <i>edge</i> within a directed cyclic state-identity graph. We say <i>cyclic</i> because a program might usefully loop through the same combination of state variables, values, and effector configurations (a <i>vertex</i> in the program state-identity graph). Even an infinite loop can be useful—consider, for example, a program that waits for a request, and responds, forever.</p> 
  <p>Even in a purely functional programming paradigm, where useful work might simply involve recursion or tail-recursion in which the evolving state variables are all hidden on the stack and may not even have names, the program state is still evolving. So, it is not only side effects on visible state that must be considered as program state identities are counted, but also hidden state. Some evolving state is invisible but implied—consider the CPU's program counter, whose runtime value is almost never of concern to the logic of the program, but whose semantic value is inherent in the structure of the programs, meaning: <i>here</i>, because it must presently be so.</p> 
  <p>&nbsp;</p> 
  <h3>Correctness</h3> 
  <p>It is axiomatic that all programs ought to be constructed in such a way that incorrect behavior is avoided. Care must be taken to detect and handle error conditions arising from any of a program's operations, where <i>to handle</i> might simply mean to signal failure and abort, or it might mean mitigating the error condition through some retry or fallback strategy. In most cases, a program should not continue to operate normally after some antecedent operation completes nonusefully, unless that operation was in some way optional.</p> 
  <p>Theory predicts that a programmer could, after any state modifying operation, inspect all then-visible state variable values and all state effectors to verify that the total program state corresponds to a defined and acceptable identity. This is unwise for three reasons. First, it requires a lot of coding effort to do correctly; second, it's a lot of operations for the computer to execute at beneficial granularity; and third, inspection correctness will inevitably rot over time as the program itself evolves. Fortunately, there is an easier way to maintain definedness, which is to inspect inputs and outputs across abstraction boundaries to account for all knowable side effects and, crucially, avoid operations having undefined outcomes.</p> 
  <p>Program state definedness is therefore a vital property of correctness. Put simply, if a program enters an undefined state, that program should abort as soon as possible, performing only the minimum viable housekeeping. Once in an undefined state, there is no way back to definedness—meaning that no operation the program performs can be trusted. Even a full or partial restart is unreliable unless performed by the program's external invoker. A program that can enter an undefined state is incorrect and will require revision. Aborting as soon as possible will accelerate the diagnostic and revision process, as well as reduce hallucinatory outcomes.</p> 
  <p>&nbsp;</p> 
  <h3>Examples in C</h3> 
  <p>Originally designed as a portable systems programming language for operating-system construction, C had to provide ways to express low-level logic patterns such as pointer arithmetic. Designed for 16-bit computers of the late 1960s, it could not afford the overhead of safety features such as bounds checking or reference counting. This led to an approach that enabled the fastest technology growth in recorded history, during which time every programmer had to learn the hard way how to be careful about software engineering safety practices. At scale, now, there are always enough new C programmers still learning about software safety to create an endless supply of trouble, and, for this reason, any program that can be successfully expressed in a higher-level programming language ought to be.</p> 
  <p>Consider pointer casting of integer variables.</p> 
  <p><code>(char *)&amp;ival</code> yields a pointer that, on modern "little endian" computer hardware such as AMD64 and ARM processors, accesses the low-order octet of a multibyte integer and, if dereferenced, will allow values from zero to 0xFF to be stored or retrieved. On older "big endian" hardware such as MC68000, PowerPC, SPARC, and MIPS, this pointer instead accesses the high-order octet of a multibyte integer, allowing only values that are multiples of 2<sup>24</sup> from zero to 0xFF000000 if 32-bit or else multiples of 2<sup>56</sup> from zero to 0xFF00000000000000 if 64-bit. The compiler will be silent on the matter. Quite aside from undefinedness resulting if the multibyte integer has nonzero values in its other three octets, the program state identity after such a reference is at best pseudo-defined—the program might silently work—until it silently does not.</p> 
  <p>Consider the <code>gets()</code> standard library function, which reads characters from the standard input stream until a line termination character or "end of file" is encountered, storing each character in a successive memory location, beginning at a pointer supplied by its caller. Notably, the caller does not provide a boundary parameter, and if the standard input stream contains too many characters, these are stored right on top of other variables, possibly including the stack frame, trampling the hidden variables within. Famously (see <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Morris_worm">MorrisWorm</a>), this design vulnerability was used in the first Internet worm where, with careful stream construction, it was possible to deliver an artificial stack frame with a new series of machine-level CPU instructions that would spawn a shell. This is now called a <i>stack smash</i>, which is one of many forms of memory unsafety whereby a program can enter an undefined state. A program that could ever call <code>gets()</code> is defective by definition.</p> 
  <p>Consider the <code>strcpy(), strncpy(), strlcpy(), strcat(), strncat(),</code> and <code>strlcat()</code> standard library functions. Two of these aren't told the size of the destination memory region and can rarely be verified for correctness. Two are told the destination size but will not add a terminating NUL character unless the source string is short enough and so can never be verified for correctness. Two will add the terminating NUL even if the source string is overlong—unless the destination size is zero, and so can only sometimes be verified for correctness. In all cases, overlap between the source string and destination region results in undefined behavior. </p> 
  <p>The <code>sprintf()</code> and <code>snprintf()</code> functions have similar shortcomings. In all cases where truncation occurs, it is up to the caller to detect this. Silent truncation is often an undefined program state since the truncated string might actually be used for some purpose other than display. A safe interface for string functions of this kind would not permit unsized destination regions, would abort if given a zero-sized destination region or overlapping strings, and would generate empty strings upon truncation in order to encourage the caller to check for truncation conditions rather than continuing blindly.</p> 
  <p>Lastly for C, consider <code>malloc(), free(),</code> and <code>realloc()</code>. These functions create, destroy, and resize objects in the heap. For performance reasons, newly created heap objects are uninitialized, which can leak information from earlier heap objects, and destroyed or resized heap objects are not reinitialized, which makes that information leakable to future heap objects. Worse still, the address of a heap object is known only by value—so, upon destruction, that value will remain briefly available to the program, easily leading to a "use after <code>free()</code>" or "double <code>free()</code>" condition, which are forms of undefined program state. </p> 
  <p>A resized heap object might move, in which case it is up to the program to update all references to that object, but this housekeeping is frequently left undone—a "use after <code>realloc()</code>" condition, though often referred to as a "use after <code>free()</code>" problem. A safe interface would at minimum reinitialize both the heap object and the reference pointer upon destruction or resizing. No part of the C programming language environment better demonstrates irrational confidence in program state identity than <code>malloc(), free(),</code> and <code>realloc()</code>.</p> 
  <p>&nbsp;</p> 
  <h3>An Example from POSIX</h3> 
  <p>The great power of Unix and the systems that evolved from it is composability. Most features are meant to be stacked or chained together, and no barriers exist that aren't absolutely required for correctness or security. In that spirit, let us turn our attention to the <code>popen()</code> and <code>system()</code> functions in the standard library. Each creates a subprocess, executing a shell-level command given as a string—effectively promoting data to code. When the command string is a compile-time constant, it is possible to shallowly validate at compile time that it doesn't have harmful effects or potentially dangerous side effects. We say "shallowly" because it is not possible at compile time to know the full characteristics of every system where the command could execute. </p> 
  <p>The real problem, however, is worse—the string might not be a compile-time constant but rather be composed using string concatenation or a template where some components are learned at runtime such as by command-line argument or external input or configuration values. A safe interface would at minimum accept an array of argument strings and would bypass the shell. Because of composability, however, it would still be possible to declare the shell as the target command and the intended command as an argument to that shell invocation. Relative safety comes by convention—use of constant strings with no composition possible—but such conventions are difficult to enforce in a long-lived project associated with generational teams. After calling <code>popen()</code> or <code>system()</code>, there is no reason for confidence as to the state identity of either the running program or the system where it runs.</p> 
  <p>&nbsp;</p> 
  <h3>We've Got to Talk about EVAL()</h3> 
  <p>Promoting data to code always creates a separation-of-concerns problem where it is approximately impossible for the program to ensure that there will be no code-level misinterpretation of the input data. Scripting languages such as Perl, Python, and JavaScript allow the promotion of arbitrary string data into full-featured language source code using a function called <code>eval()</code>. It is possible to specify a compile-time constant as the string to be evaluated, and, in such cases, the intended program fragment can be verified as to intent and safety by the programmer or toolchain. </p> 
  <p>It is, however, quite common to construct the string at runtime using concatenation and templates and to include as components various values unknowable at compile time. Often, an attempt is made to restrict the range and pattern of such inputs (sanitization), but that's an iterative cat-and-mouse game, because the scripting language interpreter might gain new features over time, turning today's safe value into tomorrow's time bomb. In a program designed to be used in a confined and sheltered environment, the flexibility of <code>eval()</code> might equal or exceed its risks. Although meant to be used by third parties or exposed to the open Internet, <code>eval()</code> of a runtime-composed string is a recipe for disaster since there is no constraint as to what the program state will be afterward.</p> 
  <p>&nbsp;</p> 
  <h3>Little Johnny Tables</h3> 
  <p>A less transparent separation-of-concerns problem similar to <code>eval()</code> was made famous by an xkcd webcomic showing how an enterprising mom had entered <code>`); DELETE TABLE Students;</code> as her son's last name when registering at the school. We all hoped that the school had a recent backup of the Students database, but ultimately this comic proved to be of the funny-because-true variety. Sanitizing the inputs might have helped prevent this data loss, but the real purposes of input sanity are user experience and data quality. Where that school's software-engineering practices were shoddy was in passing runtime values into an SQL parser. </p> 
  <p>Experience here is measured in tire marks down one's backside, and eventually every programmer learns to quote their runtime values against the possibility of interpretation by whatever library or agent they're transmitted to. A rarefied minority of programmers learns to parameterize their runtime values so they need not be quoted and because of innate opacity. The world cannot afford to have each programmer learn each lesson the hard way either through operations or code review. Rather, the software engineering community must outright remove or restrict the silliest of dangerous ways to express program logic.</p> 
  <p>&nbsp;</p> 
  <h3>Mitigation?</h3> 
  <p>When dangerous features of old programming language and operating systems are discussed, it is normally part of a conversation about why we ought to be using newer programming languages or operating systems, and this is not without merit—merely naive. The world has gone digital, and very few software supply chains are well understood; the long tail is very long and no one will succeed at a task such as "rewrite everything in Rust (or Go)" even if that certainly would yield a safer world. </p> 
  <p>Many billions of lines of code add many forks—many of which are disconnected from their upstreams and some of which exist only in compiled form because of lost source code or toolchains. Thus, any planned software-engineering safety practices must reward investment in not only better languages and environments, but also better tools with which to detect and prevent opportunities for existing programs to enter undefined states. It matters little that the total cost of mitigation would be less if we could somehow rewrite everything everywhere all at once. Software creators are necessarily limited in how much work they can do at any given moment, and the gradual narrowing of the paths to undefinedness across the software ecosystem has been more relevant than the combined aggregate of all attempts to start over from scratch.</p> 
  <p>Fortunately, computers keep getting faster and cheaper, and tools once considered fantasy continue to enter reality. The static analysis tools for software are stronger now (2026, a few years into the age of generative AI) than they have ever been, and software creators should be investigating their options. Perhaps data-flow analysis across a large suite of software could detect that a heap object has been destroyed or relocated while many pointers to the old heap object still exist. Perhaps C could evolve just a bit further so developers could move from unbounded arrays to bounded slices and kill with fire the NUL terminated strings they have been using. </p> 
  <p>This article has barely scratched the surface of the dangerous software engineering practices that occasion the world's ongoing data losses and increasing digital vulnerability. What each software creator actually does will depend on their resources and priorities—which are usually: (1) time to market; (2) competitiveness; and (3) profitability. In the generative AI era, resources are getting a boost, and the winners of the next round of the great digital game will be those who find a way to make safety a priority.</p> 
  <p>&nbsp;</p> 
  <h3>Conclusion</h3> 
  <p>We are unlikely to make differences we cannot name, and the main purpose of this article is to provide a way to talk about, and thus a way to think about, the larger-scoped forces shaping both the history and opportunities of software engineering safety. Today's AI coding assistants augur an era when more software will be created than ever before and by more people and agents than ever before. It's undecided as yet whether this era will be safer or more dangerous than the last. Undecided by us, that is. If we merely produce more software faster, the likely outcome should worry us. If we add a focus on automated techniques relying on modern computing that can detect and prevent opportunities for software to enter undefined states, we would make an important and competitive problem <i>investable</i>.</p> 
  <p>&nbsp;</p> 
